## 4.2 LinkedList

### Internal Structure (Doubly Linked List)

```
null ← [prev|"A"|next] ↔ [prev|"B"|next] ↔ [prev|"C"|next] → null
         ↑head                                      ↑tail
```

Each **Node** contains:
```java
private static class Node<E> {
    E item;
    Node<E> next;
    Node<E> prev;
}
```

LinkedList maintains references to:
- `first` → head node
- `last` → tail node
- `size` → count

---

### LinkedList Time Complexity

| Operation | Time Complexity | Reason |
|-----------|----------------|--------|
| `add(E e)` at end | **O(1)** | Direct tail reference |
| `add(int i, E e)` | **O(n)** | Traverse to index i |
| `get(int i)` | **O(n)** | No index → must traverse |
| `remove(int i)` | **O(n)** | Traverse + pointer update |
| `addFirst()` / `addLast()` | **O(1)** | Direct head/tail access |
| `removeFirst()` / `removeLast()` | **O(1)** | Direct head/tail access |
| `contains(Object o)` | **O(n)** | Linear search |

---

### LinkedList Code Examples

```java
import java.util.LinkedList;

LinkedList<String> ll = new LinkedList<>();

// Adding
ll.add("B");            // add at end
ll.addFirst("A");       // add at head → [A, B]
ll.addLast("C");        // add at tail → [A, B, C]
ll.add(1, "X");         // add at index → [A, X, B, C]

// Accessing
ll.get(0);              // "A" — O(n)!
ll.getFirst();          // "A" — O(1)
ll.getLast();           // "C" — O(1)
ll.peek();              // peeks at head (same as getFirst)
ll.peekFirst();
ll.peekLast();

// Removing
ll.remove();            // removes head
ll.removeFirst();       // removes head
ll.removeLast();        // removes tail
ll.remove(1);           // removes at index 1
ll.remove("X");         // removes by value
ll.poll();              // removes head, returns null if empty

// Queue operations
ll.offer("D");          // enqueue at tail
ll.poll();              // dequeue from head

// Stack operations
ll.push("Z");           // pushes at head
ll.pop();               // pops from head
```

---

### LinkedList: Advantages vs Disadvantages

| Advantages | Disadvantages |
|------------|---------------|
| O(1) insert/delete at head/tail | O(n) random access |
| No resizing needed | Extra memory per node (prev + next) |
| Efficient as Queue and Stack | Poor cache performance |
| No shifting of elements | |

---

### LinkedList Interview Questions

> ❓ **Q: When should you use LinkedList over ArrayList?**
> ✅ **A:** When you frequently add/remove at the beginning or middle. For random access, ArrayList is better.

> ❓ **Q: LinkedList implements which interfaces?**
> ✅ **A:** List, Deque, Queue, Cloneable, Serializable

> ❓ **Q: Is LinkedList thread-safe?**
> ✅ **A:** No. Use `Collections.synchronizedList()`.

> ❓ **Q: Does LinkedList allow null?**
> ✅ **A:** Yes, multiple nulls allowed.

