## 4.4 Stack

Stack is a **LIFO** (Last In First Out) data structure. It extends Vector.

```
push("A") → push("B") → push("C")

     TOP
  ┌─────┐
  │  C  │ ← peek() returns C; pop() removes C
  ├─────┤
  │  B  │
  ├─────┤
  │  A  │
  └─────┘
  BOTTOM
```

### Stack Methods

```java
import java.util.Stack;

Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

stack.push(1);        // pushes 1
stack.push(2);        // pushes 2
stack.push(3);        // pushes 3

stack.peek();         // 3 — view top without removing
stack.pop();          // 3 — removes and returns top
stack.empty();        // false — is stack empty?
stack.search(1);      // 2 — returns 1-based position from top (or -1)
stack.size();         // 2
```

### Stack Time Complexity

| Operation | Time |
|-----------|------|
| `push()` | O(1) |
| `pop()` | O(1) |
| `peek()` | O(1) |
| `search()` | O(n) |
| `empty()` | O(1) |

> ⚠️ **Interview Tip:** "Prefer `ArrayDeque` over `Stack`. Stack extends Vector (legacy, synchronized). ArrayDeque is faster and not thread-safe, which is fine for single-threaded use."

```java
// Preferred modern approach:
Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
stack.push(1);    // addFirst
stack.pop();      // removeFirst
stack.peek();     // peekFirst
```

