# SECTION 5: SET INTERFACE

## 5.1 HashSet

### Internal Working

HashSet is backed by a **HashMap** internally!

```java
// Internally, HashSet is:
private transient HashMap<E,Object> map;
private static final Object PRESENT = new Object();

public boolean add(E e) {
    return map.put(e, PRESENT) == null;
}
```

So when you add "Apple" to a HashSet, it does:
`hashMap.put("Apple", PRESENT)`

### How Hashing Works

```
add("Apple")
    ↓
hash("Apple") → hashCode = 63476538
    ↓
bucket = hashCode % capacity → bucket 3
    ↓
[bucket 3] → [Apple → PRESENT]
```

```
add("Banana")
    ↓
hash("Banana") → hashCode = 1982479668
    ↓
bucket = hashCode % capacity → bucket 7
    ↓
[bucket 7] → [Banana → PRESENT]
```

If another element hashes to same bucket = **Collision** (handled by chaining/tree)

---

### HashSet Time Complexity

| Operation | Average | Worst Case |
|-----------|---------|------------|
| `add(E e)` | O(1) | O(n) — many collisions |
| `remove(Object o)` | O(1) | O(n) |
| `contains(Object o)` | O(1) | O(n) |
| `size()` | O(1) | O(1) |

---

### HashSet Code Examples

```java
HashSet<String> set = new HashSet<>();

set.add("Apple");
set.add("Banana");
set.add("Apple");    // duplicate — ignored
set.add(null);       // null allowed (once)

System.out.println(set.size());           // 3
System.out.println(set.contains("Apple")); // true

set.remove("Banana");

// Iteration (no guaranteed order)
for (String s : set) {
    System.out.println(s);
}

// Set operations
Set<String> set2 = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList("Apple", "Cherry"));

// Union
set.addAll(set2);

// Intersection
set.retainAll(set2);

// Difference
set.removeAll(set2);
```

| Feature | HashSet |
|---------|---------|
| Ordering | ❌ No order |
| Sorted | ❌ No |
| Duplicates | ❌ Not allowed |
| Null | ✅ One null allowed |
| Thread-safe | ❌ No |

---

## 5.2 LinkedHashSet

- Extends HashSet
- Maintains **insertion order** using a doubly linked list + hash table

```java
LinkedHashSet<String> lhs = new LinkedHashSet<>();
lhs.add("Banana");
lhs.add("Apple");
lhs.add("Cherry");
lhs.add("Apple"); // duplicate, ignored

// Prints in insertion order: Banana, Apple, Cherry
for (String s : lhs) System.out.println(s);
```

| Feature | HashSet | LinkedHashSet |
|---------|---------|---------------|
| Ordering | ❌ Random | ✅ Insertion order |
| Performance | ✅ Slightly faster | ❌ Slightly slower (linked list overhead) |
| Memory | ✅ Less | ❌ More |

---

## 5.3 TreeSet

### Internal Working
TreeSet is backed by a **TreeMap**, which uses a **Red-Black Tree** (self-balancing BST).

```
TreeSet<Integer>: add(5), add(3), add(7), add(1), add(4)

        5
       / \
      3   7
     / \
    1   4

Inorder traversal: 1, 3, 4, 5, 7  → SORTED!
```

### TreeSet Code Examples

```java
TreeSet<Integer> ts = new TreeSet<>();
ts.add(5);
ts.add(3);
ts.add(7);
ts.add(1);

// Always sorted ascending
System.out.println(ts);     // [1, 3, 5, 7]

// Navigation methods (TreeSet specific)
ts.first();                 // 1 — smallest
ts.last();                  // 7 — largest
ts.higher(3);               // 5 — strictly greater than 3
ts.lower(5);                // 3 — strictly less than 5
ts.ceiling(4);              // 5 — >= 4
ts.floor(4);                // 3 — <= 4
ts.headSet(5);              // [1, 3] — less than 5
ts.tailSet(5);              // [5, 7] — >= 5
ts.subSet(3, 7);            // [3, 5] — from 3 (incl) to 7 (excl)

// Descending
TreeSet<Integer> desc = new TreeSet<>(Collections.reverseOrder());
```

### TreeSet Time Complexity

| Operation | Time |
|-----------|------|
| `add(E e)` | O(log n) |
| `remove(Object o)` | O(log n) |
| `contains(Object o)` | O(log n) |
| `first()` / `last()` | O(log n) |
| Iteration | O(n) |

> ⚠️ TreeSet does NOT allow null (throws NullPointerException)

> ⚠️ TreeSet elements must be Comparable, or you must provide a Comparator

