# SECTION 6: QUEUE INTERFACE

## 6.1 PriorityQueue

### Internal Working: Min-Heap

PriorityQueue uses a **Binary Min-Heap** internally (backed by array).

```
PriorityQueue (Min-Heap):
add(5), add(1), add(3), add(7), add(2)

          1          ← always the smallest at top
         / \
        2   3
       / \
      7   5

Array: [1, 2, 3, 7, 5]
```

- **poll()** always removes the **smallest** element (min-heap by default)
- For max-heap, use `Comparator.reverseOrder()`

### PriorityQueue Code Examples

```java
// Min Heap (default)
PriorityQueue<Integer> minPQ = new PriorityQueue<>();
minPQ.offer(5);
minPQ.offer(1);
minPQ.offer(3);

minPQ.peek();   // 1 — smallest, does not remove
minPQ.poll();   // 1 — removes smallest
minPQ.poll();   // 3
minPQ.poll();   // 5

// Max Heap
PriorityQueue<Integer> maxPQ = new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());
maxPQ.offer(5);
maxPQ.offer(1);
maxPQ.offer(3);
maxPQ.poll();   // 5 — largest first

// Custom objects with Comparator
PriorityQueue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> a[1] - b[1]); // sort by 2nd element

// PriorityQueue does NOT guarantee order during iteration!
// Use poll() to get sorted order
while (!minPQ.isEmpty()) {
    System.out.print(minPQ.poll() + " ");  // 1 3 5
}
```

### PriorityQueue Time Complexity

| Operation | Time |
|-----------|------|
| `offer(E e)` | O(log n) |
| `poll()` | O(log n) |
| `peek()` | O(1) |
| `contains(Object o)` | O(n) |
| `size()` | O(1) |

