# SECTION 8: HASHING — COMPLETE CONCEPT

## 8.1 What is Hashing?

Hashing is the process of **converting an object to an integer** (hashCode) to determine where to store/find it.

**Real-world Analogy:**
> Think of a large hotel with 100 rooms (buckets). When a guest (object) arrives, the receptionist uses a formula (hashCode) to assign a room number. When you want to find the guest, you use the same formula to directly go to the room instead of checking all 100 rooms.

## 8.2 hashCode() and equals() Contract

```
THE CONTRACT:
If a.equals(b) == true   →   a.hashCode() == b.hashCode()   (MUST be true)
If a.hashCode() == b.hashCode()   →   a.equals(b) may or may not be true
```

**Critical Rule:**
- If you override `equals()`, you MUST override `hashCode()`
- If two objects are equal, they MUST have the same hashCode

```java
class Student {
    String name;
    int age;

    // Without this, hashMap won't find your Student correctly!
    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (this == o) return true;
        if (!(o instanceof Student)) return false;
        Student s = (Student) o;
        return age == s.age && Objects.equals(name, s.name);
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return Objects.hash(name, age);  // use all fields used in equals
    }
}
```

---

## 8.3 Collision

**Collision** = Two different objects hash to the **same bucket**.

```
"apple".hashCode() % 16 = bucket 5
"grape".hashCode() % 16 = bucket 5   → COLLISION!

Bucket 5: ["apple"→1] → ["grape"→5]  (linked list / tree)
```

**Collision Resolution in HashMap:**
- **Chaining:** Multiple entries in same bucket (Java uses this)
- **Open Addressing:** Find next empty bucket (Java does NOT use this)

---

## 8.4 Load Factor

```
Load Factor = n / capacity
Where n = number of entries, capacity = number of buckets

Default Load Factor = 0.75

Example:
  Initial capacity = 16
  Rehash threshold = 16 × 0.75 = 12

  After 12 entries → REHASH!
  → New capacity = 32 (doubled)
  → All entries rehashed into new buckets
  → Old array garbage collected
```

**Why 0.75?**
- Too low (e.g., 0.5) → frequent rehashing → bad performance
- Too high (e.g., 1.0) → too many collisions → bad performance
- 0.75 is a **balanced trade-off** between time and space

---

## 8.5 Rehashing

```
Before Rehash (capacity=16, load=0.75, threshold=12):
  buckets: [0..15], 12 entries spread across buckets

After Rehash (capacity=32):
  New array with 32 buckets
  Each entry's bucket recalculated: index = hash & (32-1)
  Old entries redistributed → fewer collisions
```

---

## 8.6 Hashing Interview Questions

> ❓ **Q: What is the hashCode of null?**
> ✅ **A:** 0 (Java maps null keys to bucket 0 in HashMap)

> ❓ **Q: Can two objects have same hashCode but not be equal?**
> ✅ **A:** Yes! This is a collision. hashCode equality doesn't imply object equality.

> ❓ **Q: What happens if hashCode always returns 1 for all objects?**
> ✅ **A:** All objects go to the same bucket. Effectively a linked list. O(n) for all operations. Very bad.

> ❓ **Q: Why does Java 8 convert to Tree when bucket size ≥ 8?**
> ✅ **A:** To prevent O(n) worst case. With a tree, worst case becomes O(log n).

