# SECTION 9: COMPARABLE VS COMPARATOR

## 9.1 Comparable Interface

- Package: `java.lang`
- Method: `int compareTo(T o)`
- Defines the **natural ordering** of objects
- The class itself implements Comparable ("this" vs "other")

```java
class Student implements Comparable<Student> {
    String name;
    int marks;

    public Student(String name, int marks) {
        this.name = name;
        this.marks = marks;
    }

    @Override
    public int compareTo(Student other) {
        return this.marks - other.marks;  // ascending by marks
        // negative → this comes first
        // zero     → equal
        // positive → other comes first
    }
}

List<Student> students = new ArrayList<>();
students.add(new Student("Alice", 85));
students.add(new Student("Bob", 92));
students.add(new Student("Charlie", 78));

Collections.sort(students);  // uses compareTo
// Charlie(78), Alice(85), Bob(92)
```

---

## 9.2 Comparator Interface

- Package: `java.util`
- Method: `int compare(T o1, T o2)`
- Defines **external/custom ordering** — class doesn't need to change
- Can create multiple different ordering strategies

```java
// Sort by name
Comparator<Student> byName = new Comparator<Student>() {
    public int compare(Student a, Student b) {
        return a.name.compareTo(b.name);
    }
};

// Sort by marks descending (lambda)
Comparator<Student> byMarksDesc = (a, b) -> b.marks - a.marks;

// Sort by marks, then by name
Comparator<Student> byMarksThenName = Comparator
    .comparingInt((Student s) -> s.marks)
    .thenComparing(s -> s.name);

Collections.sort(students, byName);
Collections.sort(students, byMarksDesc);
students.sort(byMarksThenName);

// TreeSet with custom Comparator
TreeSet<Student> ts = new TreeSet<>(byName);

// PriorityQueue with custom Comparator
PriorityQueue<Student> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(byMarksDesc);
```

---

## 9.3 Comparable vs Comparator — Master Comparison

| Feature | Comparable | Comparator |
|---------|------------|------------|
| Package | `java.lang` | `java.util` |
| Method | `compareTo(T o)` | `compare(T o1, T o2)` |
| Modify class? | ✅ Yes (class must implement it) | ❌ No (external class) |
| Multiple orderings? | ❌ No (one natural order) | ✅ Yes (many strategies) |
| Modifies original class | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| Usage | `Collections.sort(list)` | `Collections.sort(list, comparator)` |
| Used in TreeSet/TreeMap | ✅ Default ordering | ✅ Custom ordering |
| Lambda friendly? | ❌ Not directly | ✅ Yes (functional interface) |

---

## 9.4 Interview Questions

> ❓ **Q: When to use Comparable vs Comparator?**
> ✅ **A:** Use Comparable when there's one natural ordering (e.g., Student by marks). Use Comparator when you need multiple orderings or can't modify the class.

> ❓ **Q: What does compareTo return?**
> ✅ **A:** Negative if `this < other`, 0 if equal, positive if `this > other`.

> ❓ **Q: Can we use lambda for Comparator?**
> ✅ **A:** Yes! Comparator is a functional interface. `(a, b) -> a.marks - b.marks`

