# SECTION 10: ITERATION METHODS

## 10.1 All Ways to Iterate Collections

### 1. Traditional for loop (only for List/index-based)
```java
for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) {
    System.out.println(list.get(i));
}
// Use when: you need index, or modifying during iteration (with care)
```

### 2. Enhanced for loop (for-each)
```java
for (String s : list) {
    System.out.println(s);
}
// Use when: simple read-only iteration
// Cannot remove during iteration → ConcurrentModificationException!
```

### 3. Iterator
```java
Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();
while (it.hasNext()) {
    String s = it.next();
    if (s.equals("Apple")) {
        it.remove();  // SAFE removal during iteration
    }
}
// Use when: you need to remove elements during iteration
```

### 4. ListIterator (List only — bidirectional)
```java
ListIterator<String> lit = list.listIterator();
while (lit.hasNext()) {
    String s = lit.next();
    lit.set("Modified");    // can modify current element
    lit.add("New");         // can add element
}
// Backwards:
while (lit.hasPrevious()) {
    System.out.println(lit.previous());
}
// Use when: you need to modify or traverse backwards
```

### 5. forEach() with lambda
```java
list.forEach(s -> System.out.println(s));
list.forEach(System.out::println);

map.forEach((k, v) -> System.out.println(k + "=" + v));
// Use when: clean read-only operation
// Cannot use break/continue (use return to skip)
```

### 6. Stream API
```java
list.stream()
    .filter(s -> s.startsWith("A"))
    .map(String::toUpperCase)
    .sorted()
    .forEach(System.out::println);
// Use when: functional pipeline, filtering, mapping, collecting
```

